{"type":"assistant","message":{"content":[{"text":"The problem is clear: `originalEnvValues` is set at module initialization time (before tests set the env vars in `beforeEach`), so when the test sets `LOG_LEVEL=info` and then calls `setConfig`, the `originalEnvValues.get('LOG_LEVEL')` is `undefined`.\n\nThe `resetConfig` returns false because `originalValue === undefined`.\n\nThe fix: in `resetConfig`, fall back to the current `process.env` value if the original wasn't captured (or consider the current env value as the \"original\" baseline). Actually the better fix is: for `reset`, if `originalEnvValues.get(key)` is undefined but the key exists in env, we should still allow reset (treating the current env as the reset target).\n\nWait - re-reading the test: it does `setConfig('LOG_LEVEL', 'debug')` then `resetConfig('LOG_LEVEL')` and expects the value to be `'info'` (the original). The issue is that the `originalEnvValues` map is populated at module load, not at test setup. The test sets `process.env.LOG_LEVEL = 'info'` in `beforeEach` but the module was already loaded before that.\n\nThe fix options:\n1. Change `resetConfig` to fall back to `process.env[key]` if no original found - but this would reset to the \"currently modified\" value\n2. Re-initialize `originalEnvValues` when env changes - too complex\n3. Use `process.env` at reset time as the baseline — not right  \n4. Store the pre-modification value at the time of `setConfig` if not already stored in `originalEnvValues`\n\nThe best fix: at `setConfig` time, if the key is not yet in `originalEnvValues`, store the current `process.env[key]` value as the original. This ensures the \"original\" is what it was before the first modification.","type":"text"}],"id":"req_vrtx_011CZHz3nhugur92kECzpqzz","model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","role":"assistant","stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"type":"message","usage":{"input_tokens":1039,"output_tokens":1,"cache_read_input_tokens":61540},"context_management":null},"paren